.04823025315999985, -0.017049415037035942, 0.01020776480436325, 0.00403568847104907, 0.013308132067322731, 0.004186798818409443, 0.011713657528162003, -0.005166410468518734, -0.013672880828380585, 0.024365240707993507, 0.035912156105041504, 0.012359783984720707, 0.02730407752096653, 0.045895859599113464, 0.010239028371870518, 0.014954714104533195, 0.04693800210952759, -0.026678793132305145, -0.03074313886463642, 0.005637979134917259, 0.018206192180514336, -0.03649575263261795, -0.03222297877073288, 0.04856374114751816, 0.002607956063002348, 0.01414184458553791, -0.019050324335694313, -0.002234088256955147, -0.013714566826820374, 0.01585095375776291, 0.00317592266947031, 0.035307712852954865, 0.007065711542963982, 0.017070258036255836, 0.02976352721452713, -0.00694065447896719, 0.027887675911188126, -0.018206192180514336, -0.007420039270073175, 0.022510230541229248, -0.0032723206095397472, -0.017685120925307274, -0.02544906735420227, 0.02809610404074192, 0.010775730945169926, -0.015590419061481953, 0.011995035223662853, -0.004429096356034279, -0.02428187057375908, 0.006893758196383715, 0.0025167688727378845, 0.014569121412932873, 0.036516595631837845, 0.005596293602138758, 0.03051386959850788, 0.015830110758543015]], "input": ["\"THROUGHPUT PER UNIT\":\"Throughput per unit\" is calculated as the selling price of a product minus the total variable costs associated with producing one unit of the product. This includes subtracting the direct materials cost from the selling price to determine the throughput per unit.", "\"BOTTLENECK RESOURCE HOURS AVAILABLE\":\"Bottleneck resource hours available refers to the total hours available for the bottleneck process in a given period.\"", "\"OTHER FACTORY COSTS\":\"Other factory costs include all fixed and variable costs associated with running the factory, excluding direct material costs.\"", "\"SUSTAINABILITY\":\"Sustainability\" is defined as meeting the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs. This concept emphasizes the importance of long-term environmental, social, and economic health. It is both a challenge and an opportunity for organizations.", "\"SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT\":\"Sustainable development requires organizations to consider the long-term consequences of their decisions. It involves integrating environmental, social, and governance (ESG) factors into business strategies to ensure long-term value creation and sustainability.\"", "\"ESG INFORMATION\":\"ESG (Environment, Social, and Governance) information is used by investors to gauge a business's long-term value creation potential and sustainability. It includes data on environmental impact, social responsibility, and governance practices.\"", "\"SUSTAINABILITY STRATEGY PERSPECTIVES\":\"A sustainability strategy involves building value for shareholders while contributing to a sustainable society. It requires an integrated focus on value creation from capitals, stakeholder perspectives, megatrends affecting opportunities and threats, and customer preferences.\"", "\"ROLE OF ACCOUNTANTS IN DEVELOPING SUSTAINABLE PRACTICES\":\"Accountants play a central role in driving sustainability by identifying trends and impacts, integrating natural and social capital issues into management information, assessing benefits of environmental and social matters, organizing systems for decision-making, linking to value creation, driving efficiency, providing data credibility, and communicating transparently.\"", "\"LEADERSHIP AND BUSINESS STRATEGY\":\"In the context of sustainability, leadership and business strategy involve making sustainability strategic rather than tactical, identifying the business case, facilitating leadership and commitment, engaging finance and accounting functions, and connecting sustainability to strategy, risk, and performance.\"", "\"MANAGEMENT, OPERATIONS AND ACCOUNTING\":\"This area focuses on improving the process of information and data collection, analysis, and reporting. Finance professionals work closely with sustainability professionals to generate information and analysis to support decisions and reduce the sustainability impact of products, services, and operations.\"", "\"COMMUNICATIONS, REPORTING AND DISCLOSURE\":\"Finance professionals integrate meaningful sustainability performance information into business reporting processes and disclosures. This includes developing a business reporting strategy, integrating sustainability impacts into financial reporting, and assuring sustainability disclosures and reports.\"", "\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING (EMA)\":\"Environmental management accounting (EMA) provides management with monetary and non-monetary (physical) information to understand and manage the environmental impact of the organization\u2019s activities. EMA techniques include input/output analysis, activity-based costing (ABC), and life-cycle costing.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS\":\"Relevant cost analysis\" involves identifying and analyzing costs that are directly related to a specific decision. It helps in making informed decisions by focusing on costs that will change as a result of the decision. These costs are future, incremental, and cash flows, which are affected by specific management decisions.", "\"DECISION-MAKING TECHNIQUES\":\"Decision-making techniques\" covered in this chapter include various methods and tools used to analyze and make informed business decisions. These techniques help in evaluating different options and selecting the best course of action. Specifically, decision-making techniques for dealing with risk and uncertainty include research techniques to reduce uncertainty, such as focus groups and market research. Additionally, the use of simulation, expected values, sensitivity analysis, and the techniques of maximax, maximin, and minimax regret are discussed. These techniques assist in interpreting decision trees, solving multi-stage decision problems, and calculating the value of perfect and imperfect information.", "\"SOCIAL CAPITAL\":\"Social capital refers to the networks, relationships, and norms that shape the quality and quantity of a society's social interactions. It contributes to societal well-being and economic performance by fostering cooperation and trust.\"", "\"GOVERNANCE\":\"Governance involves the structures, policies, and practices that ensure an organization operates in a legal, ethical, and transparent manner. Good governance is crucial for long-term sustainability and stakeholder trust.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}